How do you think the quality of the business program now truly compares with the national?
Oh, I think we're up there.
I think our quality of our undergraduate program is as good as... Where do you think we, in a ranking, we rank?
Oh, we're probably, you know, I think we're probably easily... Our undergraduate program quality rise among the public schools.
Yeah.
Among the public schools.
We're in the top 25.
I really do.
I really think we're...
Our problem, and the others have the same problem, is that we give too many multiple choice exams because we've got too many kids.
You know, I still try to give exams, multiple choice exams, when I got teaching two sections of 120.
It's a lot of work on my part, but I just think I get a better feel of what those kids can do.
Who are the people, the individuals who deserve the most credit for the quality of the program here?
Well, it's... Now and or in the past.
Well, if you look, you know, from... There's several audiences.

Oh, no, I'm talking about who deserves in the past, who has earned the... Who deserves to pat on the back either historically or currently for... Taking his hand?
Yeah.

Benton, I think, you know, started with Muse.
Muse, Mobley, and Benton have taken us there.

Who are the faculty members in the college who deserve the biggest pats on the back now and or in the past?
Well, I can only speak from, well, I can only speak, but again, you know, I think Lynn Berry, and I've mentioned his name.
Pete Rose and Don Frazier have always done a great job for us here.
And accounting, I don't,
I don't know who does that, but Jim Benjamin does a very good job politically of keeping A&M in front of the Arthur Andersons and the consulting firms.

Who have been your closest friends, buddies, colleagues?
On the academic side?
Probably two or three that over the years would be Dan Robertson and
Paul Bush and Dan probably are the closest.
Over the years, of course, it was with Bill Pryde, but basically those two.
Where at noon or during the work day, at noon or coffee time, where would you and a group go to talk about something important or something you just wanted to share?
We just come in here.
You know, we aren't that collegial.
You know, there's groups that go for coffee.
We don't buddy around that much.
I see, I maybe go out and eat with Dan and Robertson.
Where do you eat for lunch?
At home.
Go home for lunch.
Because Patty and I can talk about the day.
And if I have other things to do, I'll bring my lunch.
You know, eat in there with the secretaries.
And I enjoy eating with the secretaries, you know.
Share with this machine two or three anecdotes that are unique to your experience and or Texas A&M.
Well, I think one of them that I've shared with you that I just love was when I was teaching a class.

For example, the St.

But another one was the Centennial Committee that you chaired.

Yeah, I've got another panel.

Oh, yeah, it's patina.

As you think back, were there any key decisions in the department or college that you now realize those were pivotal?
when you all decided to do this instead of that?
No, uh-uh.
No big change that I was—got involved in.
Well, yeah, you do a—you do a five-year—when Muse came in, we're going to do a five-year plan.
Okay, and that was— That's probably—that made us really—and we would review that semi-annually.
So he kept you focused.
It just wasn't paper.
Tell me about it.
Where are we going?
What should we change?
Why can't we do what we're doing?
Yeah.

You know, I've thought about that.
I think everybody thought that because, you know, they think sometimes you might have some money.

That's the easiest place to go.
You can decide.
No, but you'd struggle with that.
You would struggle with that.

I've even thought of just giving unrestricted funds to the department head of marketing and say, there's a million bucks, put in foundation, it'll scrape off $50,000 a year, hard cash.

you just report to the dean how you use it uh for the for the good of the department for the good of the department the other place that i would probably give it is for the fellows program our cba fellows program undergraduates it's underfunded and uh it's probably underfunded by that much fifty thousand dollar a million dollar endowment fifty thousand dollars a year

As much as this is a land-grant school, I do wish we were more selective.
I do wish we would, rather than certify, because we got a lot of kids in here who just want to be certified, and this is what disappoints me.
I can go into class today, and I can tell you probably within three class periods who wants to be certified and who wants to work.
And I wish I could say, okay, you guys that want to be certified,
Here's the only thing you have to do.
All you gotta do is pass the exams.
Don't even have to come in class, just pass the exams.
Don't have to participate in this, don't have to do all this other stuff that we, and I press them pretty hard, and you're gonna get a D. Now get out.
Because they really don't, they detract from the quality of the class.
We have a lot of kids that want to succeed, and we have a lot of kids that just want to be certified, don't want to be educated.
They're here for the ring because the ring's going to give them the job.
Not very many, but enough that it's a disappointment.
But I love this school.
